<br>
<br>
Oberth first popularized the idea of space travel as a real possibility with his 1923 pamphlet, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   Die Rakete zu den Planetenraumen</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (The Rocket into Planetary Space). This work directly inspired the creation of the German VfR (&quot;Verein fur Raumschiffahrt,&quot; the Society for Spaceship Travel) which was the genesis of the German rocket programs of the World War 2 era. Oberth died in 1989 at the age of 95**, having lived to see many of his ideas become spectacular reality.<br>
<br>
*the link is a student's paper that summarizes information contained in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   History of Rocketry and Space Travel</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by Wernher von Braun and Frederick Ordway III.<br>
My copy of this book, btw, is a limited edition with leather binding, slick paper etc. It is also hand-signed by both authors and is one of my most treasured possessions.<br>
**Note that Oberth died on his birthday, which was also new year's day. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A> at: 7/18/02 1:56:01 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 161<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/18/02 1:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=308.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Visionaries</span><hr size=1> To really understand what kind of visionary Clarke was, and still is, it is probably necessary to read the two anthologies of his non-fiction work, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Ascent to Orbit</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->(1984) and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Greetings, Carbon-Based Bipeds!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->(1999). These are chronological records of Sir Arthur's thoughts on many subjects, beginning with his very first forays into public discourse during his teens. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Ascent to Orbit</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> concentrates on his scientific papers, including the famous 1945 article in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wireless World</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (&quot;Extra-terrestrial Relays&quot;) that postulated the development of geostationary communications satellites. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Greetings, Carbon-Based Bipeds!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is a more general record that includes some of the same material as the earlier book. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uatomicredux.showPublicProfile?lang